# npm Hygiene

## Policy

**Never run `npm install` or `npm ci` directly on the host machine.** All npm/Node commands for `backend/` run inside Docker via `scripts/backend-docker.sh`. This keeps `node_modules` off the host filesystem and Node out of the global environment.

CI (GitHub Actions) is the source of truth for passing tests — pushing triggers `npm ci && typecheck && vitest` automatically.

## How to run backend commands

```bash
# First-time / after package.json changes — generates package-lock.json
./scripts/backend-docker.sh "npm install"

# Default (same as CI): npm ci + typecheck + test
./scripts/backend-docker.sh

# Custom command
./scripts/backend-docker.sh "npm test"
```

## When package.json changes

Always run `./scripts/backend-docker.sh "npm install"` after editing `package.json`, then **commit the updated `package-lock.json`**. CI uses `npm ci` which requires a committed lockfile.

## What NOT to do

- ❌ `npm install` in the terminal on the host
- ❌ `npm install -g` for any backend tooling
- ❌ Committing `backend/node_modules/` (it is gitignored)
- ❌ Running `npm install` as part of an agent task without flagging it first

## Secrets rule (related)

`FAL_KEY`, `UPSTASH_REDIS_REST_URL`, and `UPSTASH_REDIS_REST_TOKEN` live **only in Vercel server-side env vars**. Never in client-side code, never committed.
